```python
import math
def logsumexp(z):
    m = max(z); return m + math.log(sum(math.exp(x-m) for x in z))
def cross_entropy(logits, true):
    return -(logits[true] - logsumexp(logits))

print(round(cross_entropy([2.0, 1.0, 0.1], 0), 4))   # 0.4170
```

Cross-entropy for a one-hot target reduces to **−log P(correct class)** — exactly the negative log-likelihood. Minimizing it pushes the probability mass of the true class toward 1. Computing it from logits via log-sum-exp (instead of softmax-then-log) keeps it numerically stable, which is why `CrossEntropyLoss` takes raw logits, not probabilities.
